00:11:56.280 --> 00:11:57.497 align:middle line:90%
What is a Venus transit?

00:11:57.497 --> 00:11:59.580 align:middle line:84%
>>HOAGLAND: Well, in
essence, it's a mini eclipse.

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:00.500 align:middle line:90%
>>JAY: Yeah.

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:02.570 align:middle line:84%
>>HOAGLAND: This is a
plot that was put out

00:12:02.570 --> 00:12:06.000 align:middle line:84%
by NASA some years
ago, before 2003.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.310 align:middle line:84%
Because of the
Venus orbit, you can

00:12:08.310 --> 00:12:11.710 align:middle line:84%
get these transits of
the disc of Venus, which

00:12:11.710 --> 00:12:13.590 align:middle line:84%
is a planet the
size of the Earth,

00:12:13.590 --> 00:12:17.790 align:middle line:84%
25 million miles away between
us and the sun during a transit.

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:20.030 align:middle line:84%
In this shot, on the
right, you see Venus

00:12:20.030 --> 00:12:22.220 align:middle line:90%
during the 2003 transit.

00:12:22.220 --> 00:12:26.150 align:middle line:84%
There are two sets of
transits eight years apart

00:12:26.150 --> 00:12:29.180 align:middle line:90%
every, roughly, 113 years.

00:12:29.180 --> 00:12:32.610 align:middle line:84%
Because of the way the orbits of
the solar system are lined up,

00:12:32.610 --> 00:12:34.840 align:middle line:84%
like here, you can see
that the orbit of Venus

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:37.594 align:middle line:84%
is not exactly in the line
with the orbit of the Earth.

00:12:37.594 --> 00:12:39.010 align:middle line:84%
So you can only
get a transit when

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:40.739 align:middle line:84%
you're at what's
called the node, which

00:12:40.739 --> 00:12:41.655 align:middle line:90%
is the crossing point.

00:12:41.655 --> 00:12:42.980 align:middle line:90%
There are two of those.

00:12:42.980 --> 00:12:46.270 align:middle line:84%
And if you watch the Earth go
around the sun on a computer

00:12:46.270 --> 00:12:49.610 align:middle line:84%
and watch Venus go around the
sun on a computer, every 113

00:12:49.610 --> 00:12:52.580 align:middle line:84%
or so years, on average,
you get an alignment

00:12:52.580 --> 00:12:54.650 align:middle line:84%
where Venus, appearing
from the Earth,

00:12:54.650 --> 00:12:56.879 align:middle line:90%
can cross the disc of the sun.

00:12:56.879 --> 00:12:58.420 align:middle line:84%
So you've got the
Earth-- in essence,

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:01.140 align:middle line:84%
a twin-- crossing 25
million miles away.

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:06.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, you can see how tiny it
appears compared to the almost

00:13:06.320 --> 00:13:08.450 align:middle line:84%
million-mile
diameter of the sun.

00:13:08.450 --> 00:13:12.970 align:middle line:84%
In theory, in the
torsion field model,

00:13:12.970 --> 00:13:15.380 align:middle line:84%
the big eclipse, which
is our own moon eclipsing

00:13:15.380 --> 00:13:20.600 align:middle line:84%
the sun on the left, and Venus
crossing the sun on the right,

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:24.940 align:middle line:84%
are two different scaled
versions of the same thing.

00:13:24.940 --> 00:13:26.540 align:middle line:84%
What we're going
to be trying to do

00:13:26.540 --> 00:13:28.750 align:middle line:84%
two weeks after
the solar eclipse

00:13:28.750 --> 00:13:31.080 align:middle line:84%
