00:20:04.310 --> 00:20:07.260 align:middle line:84%
after that, because you
can't argue with the graphs.

00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:08.760 align:middle line:90%
You can't argue with the data.

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:11.720 align:middle line:84%
What's going on with
our experiments,

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:17.050 align:middle line:84%
as went on with Allais, is
unequivocally real and cannot

00:20:17.050 --> 00:20:19.060 align:middle line:90%
be denied or gainsaid.

00:20:19.060 --> 00:20:20.220 align:middle line:90%
It's got to be answered.

00:20:20.220 --> 00:20:23.580 align:middle line:84%
And the more people who
participate in this process,

00:20:23.580 --> 00:20:25.580 align:middle line:84%
the sooner we're going
to get breakthroughs that

00:20:25.580 --> 00:20:27.340 align:middle line:84%
will lead to all
kinds of other things

00:20:27.340 --> 00:20:29.540 align:middle line:84%
that our society now
desperately needs to put to--

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:30.470 align:middle line:84%
>>JAY: We'll get to
that in a second.

00:20:30.470 --> 00:20:31.570 align:middle line:90%
That's very important.

00:20:31.570 --> 00:20:34.350 align:middle line:84%
So let's get back to the
science for a second,

00:20:34.350 --> 00:20:35.790 align:middle line:90%
so bolster our case here.

00:20:35.790 --> 00:20:39.000 align:middle line:84%
Who is Bruce De Palma,
and what did he discover?

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:40.300 align:middle line:90%
>>HOAGLAND: OK.

00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:41.370 align:middle line:90%
Here's my friend Bruce.

00:20:41.370 --> 00:20:42.410 align:middle line:90%
He's no longer with us.

00:20:42.410 --> 00:20:44.650 align:middle line:84%
He died tragically
in the early '90s.

00:20:44.650 --> 00:20:46.450 align:middle line:84%
I was very fortunate
to meet him.

00:20:46.450 --> 00:20:49.390 align:middle line:84%
He's, by the way, the brother of
Brian De Palma, the very famous

00:20:49.390 --> 00:20:51.490 align:middle line:90%
film director.

00:20:51.490 --> 00:20:53.280 align:middle line:90%
Bruce was a genius.

00:20:53.280 --> 00:20:55.350 align:middle line:84%
When he was back
at MIT, he started

00:20:55.350 --> 00:20:58.990 align:middle line:84%
looking into the properties
of rotating systems.

00:20:58.990 --> 00:21:00.310 align:middle line:90%
And he devised this experiment.

00:21:00.310 --> 00:21:04.130 align:middle line:84%
This is what's called the De
Palma spinning ball experiment.

00:21:04.130 --> 00:21:05.360 align:middle line:90%
Very simple.

00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:06.270 align:middle line:90%
He built a device.

00:21:06.270 --> 00:21:10.580 align:middle line:84%
He was a mechanical--
gentleman of all trades.

00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:12.530 align:middle line:84%
There aren't very many
experimental physicists

00:21:12.530 --> 00:21:14.390 align:middle line:84%
who are also good
theoreticians who

00:21:14.390 --> 00:21:16.348 align:middle line:84%
also are good with their
hands and can actually

00:21:16.348 --> 00:21:18.229 align:middle line:84%
go into a machine shop
and make something.

00:21:18.229 --> 00:21:19.770 align:middle line:84%
Well, he built all
the stuff himself,

00:21:19.770 --> 00:21:22.350 align:middle line:84%
because he didn't have the
money to hire a machine shop.

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:26.320 align:middle line:84%
He built a device that could
eject two balls, two steel

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:32.970 align:middle line:84%
pinballs, simultaneously,
one rotating at 27,000 RPM,

00:21:32.970 --> 00:21:34.475 align:middle line:90%
27,000 revolutions per minute--

00:21:34.475 --> 00:21:35.820 align:middle line:90%
>>JAY: That's pretty fast.

00:21:35.820 --> 00:21:38.559 align:middle line:84%
>>HOAGLAND: --the other,
stationary, simultaneously.

00:21:38.559 --> 00:21:40.350 align:middle line:84%
And then he photographed
them, because he--

00:21:40.350 --> 00:21:44.070 align:middle line:84%
when the protege of
Edwin Land at Polaroid

00:21:44.070 --> 00:21:48.290 align:middle line:84%
and a guy named Edgerton,
who would develop the strobe

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:51.220 align:middle line:84%
system of photography, where
you can make fast things

00:21:51.220 --> 00:21:54.480 align:middle line:84%
stand still by flashing
light at thousands of frames

00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:57.310 align:middle line:84%
per second-- which, by the
way, is back to your airplane

00:21:57.310 --> 00:21:58.960 align:middle line:90%
problem we'll talk about later.

00:21:58.960 --> 00:22:01.000 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so he did this
in a darkened room,

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.240 align:middle line:84%
photographed the two
balls, and noticed

00:22:03.240 --> 00:22:07.990 align:middle line:84%
that the ball that was spinning
went higher and farther

00:22:07.990 --> 00:22:10.350 align:middle line:84%
than the ball that
was not spinning.

00:22:10.350 --> 00:22:13.190 align:middle line:84%
Now, right away,
this is impossible.

00:22:13.190 --> 00:22:19.230 align:middle line:84%
In Newtonian mechanics,
rotation plays no part at all.

00:22:19.230 --> 00:22:22.250 align:middle line:84%
F equals ma, action
equals reaction, all

00:22:22.250 --> 00:22:24.430 align:middle line:90%
that, the first three laws.

00:22:24.430 --> 00:22:28.280 align:middle line:84%
So he was getting results
that were totally amazing.

00:22:28.280 --> 00:22:30.100 align:middle line:84%
He tried to go to
some very big people,

00:22:30.100 --> 00:22:32.910 align:middle line:84%
like John Wheeler at
Princeton-- black hole John

00:22:32.910 --> 00:22:34.580 align:middle line:90%
Wheeler, the big physicist.

00:22:34.580 --> 00:22:37.440 align:middle line:84%
John Wheeler literally
ushered him out of his office

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:39.810 align:middle line:84%
and closed the door,
would not talk to him.

00:22:39.810 --> 00:22:42.230 align:middle line:84%
Which indicates to me that
John Wheeler already knew this,

00:22:42.230 --> 00:22:44.380 align:middle line:84%
and it's part of
suppressed science,

00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:48.030 align:middle line:84%
because what Bruce had done is
to find from this experiment

00:22:48.030 --> 00:22:51.500 align:middle line:84%
something very correlative
to what Allais had found,

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:52.950 align:middle line:84%
which is that
rotation-- remember,

00:22:52.950 --> 00:22:57.800 align:middle line:84%
a pendulum motion
is a mini rotation--

00:22:57.800 --> 00:22:59.780 align:middle line:84%
Bruce found with
his spinning ball

00:22:59.780 --> 00:23:03.330 align:middle line:84%
that he was able to get
rotations that completely

00:23:03.330 --> 00:23:05.530 align:middle line:90%
changed inertia.

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:06.980 align:middle line:90%
He took the next step.

00:23:06.980 --> 00:23:10.220 align:middle line:84%
Then he figured out, OK, how can
I measure this scientifically?

00:23:10.220 --> 00:23:12.870 align:middle line:84%
And he went to a brand new
technology, which had just

00:23:12.870 --> 00:23:14.970 align:middle line:84%
been invented by the
Bulova Watch Company,

00:23:14.970 --> 00:23:16.410 align:middle line:90%
called the Accutron watch.

00:23:16.410 --> 00:23:19.400 align:middle line:84%
It was brought out
in '65 and still was

00:23:19.400 --> 00:23:22.320 align:middle line:84%
kind of glitzy and new and
space age and all that.

00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:27.220 align:middle line:84%
And he took this wristwatch
called the Spaceview, which

00:23:27.220 --> 00:23:30.300 align:middle line:84%
was the first new thing in
timekeeping in 300 years,

00:23:30.300 --> 00:23:32.830 align:middle line:84%
according to Bulova,
because, instead of a balance

00:23:32.830 --> 00:23:35.920 align:middle line:84%
wheel and springs and all that,
you had a little tuning fork.

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:37.950 align:middle line:84%
This is a close-up
of the tuning fork.

00:23:37.950 --> 00:23:43.570 align:middle line:84%
And it vibrated at 360
times per second, 360 Hertz.

00:23:43.570 --> 00:23:46.460 align:middle line:84%
He then took this
watch, glued it

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:50.240 align:middle line:84%
to the surface of a
Westclox, run off the grid,

00:23:50.240 --> 00:23:54.000 align:middle line:84%
above a spinning disc with
a metal shield-- that's

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.180 align:middle line:84%
that bar up in the top
there-- so you didn't get

00:23:57.180 --> 00:23:59.780 align:middle line:84%
any electromagnetic or
electrostatic effects.

00:23:59.780 --> 00:24:02.340 align:middle line:84%
He then ran it
for 1,000 seconds.

00:24:02.340 --> 00:24:06.870 align:middle line:84%
And the watch lost a second
in only 1,000 seconds.

00:24:06.870 --> 00:24:09.760 align:middle line:84%
This is the watch that's
supposed to be accurate to one

00:24:09.760 --> 00:24:12.090 align:middle line:90%
or two seconds per day.

00:24:12.090 --> 00:24:16.030 align:middle line:84%
In 1,000 seconds, 17 minutes,
it lost a full second.

00:24:16.030 --> 00:24:18.620 align:middle line:84%
He then realized-- this was
the first of many experiments--

00:24:18.620 --> 00:24:21.325 align:middle line:84%
that he had a little detector
within this vibrating tuning

00:24:21.325 --> 00:24:23.940 align:middle line:84%
fork, because the tuning
fork going back and forth

00:24:23.940 --> 00:24:27.070 align:middle line:90%
is also partial rotation.

00:24:27.070 --> 00:24:29.460 align:middle line:84%
This was a stunning
demonstration

00:24:29.460 --> 00:24:31.500 align:middle line:84%
that even a rotating
object, when

00:24:31.500 --> 00:24:34.960 align:middle line:84%
you place another rotating
object in its vicinity,

00:24:34.960 --> 00:24:37.510 align:middle line:84%
will change properties,
will change effects,

00:24:37.510 --> 00:24:43.020 align:middle line:84%
will change its response to
the invisible matrix, the ether

00:24:43.020 --> 00:24:47.060 align:middle line:84%
that is somehow being
swirled in its vicinity

00:24:47.060 --> 00:24:49.410 align:middle line:84%
just by the fact
of it's rotation.

00:24:49.410 --> 00:24:54.080 align:middle line:84%
That is how, across 25
million miles of space,

00:24:54.080 --> 00:24:57.360 align:middle line:84%
Venus can impact and
affect the Earth.

00:24:57.360 --> 00:25:01.280 align:middle line:84%
This is a breadboard now
of the Accutron system

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:06.520 align:middle line:84%
that we have devised based on De
Palma's basic experiment, which

00:25:06.520 --> 00:25:09.150 align:middle line:84%
we, of course, are going
to be using in the eclipse

00:25:09.150 --> 00:25:10.301 align:middle line:90%
measurements on Sunday.

00:25:10.301 --> 00:25:11.800 align:middle line:84%
>>JAY: Well, we'll
get back to that.

00:25:11.800 --> 00:25:13.830 align:middle line:90%
That's really fascinating.

00:25:13.830 --> 00:25:17.540 align:middle line:84%
I'm Jay Weidner, and you're
watching "Gaiam Inspirations."

00:25:17.540 --> 00:25:20.539 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to be back
here in just a couple seconds--

00:25:20.539 --> 00:25:21.580 align:middle line:90%
a couple minutes, I mean.

00:25:21.580 --> 00:25:22.836 align:middle line:90%
Thanks for watching.

00:25:22.836 --> 00:25:25.050 align:middle line:90%
